Windows Vulnerability & Hardening Auditor
Technical Implementation Documentation (Current State)
1. Project Overview
1.1 System Description

The Windows Vulnerability & Hardening Auditor is a defensive cybersecurity application that analyzes the security configuration of a local Windows system.

The application currently operates as a read-only auditing tool that inspects specific Windows security settings, evaluates them against predefined rules, and reports any detected misconfigurations along with severity classifications and remediation guidance.

The system does not modify system configurations and does not perform any exploitation. All operations are limited to safe retrieval and evaluation of configuration data.

The system is designed with extensibility in mind, allowing additional security checks to be integrated with minimal changes to the overall architecture.

The application is implemented using a multi-language architecture consisting of:

A C++ application (user interface and orchestration)
A Python-based scanning engine (security checks and rule evaluation)
PowerShell commands (data retrieval layer)
2. Current System Architecture

The system is implemented as a layered architecture, where each component has a clearly defined responsibility.

2.1 Technology Stack
Technology	Current Role
C++	Application control, UI handling, scan orchestration, JSON parsing, report generation
Python	Execution of security checks and rule evaluation
PowerShell	Retrieval of Windows configuration data
JSON	Data exchange format between Python and C++
HTML/CSS	Report generation and formatting
SQLite (Optional)	Not currently active in core workflow (reserved for future use)
3. Current System Workflow

The system follows a deterministic execution flow, where each step directly triggers the next.

Step 1 – Application Launch

The user launches the C++ application.
The application initializes:

User interface
Scan controls
Runtime environment
Step 2 – User Initiates Scan

The user selects the scan option in the interface.
This action triggers the C++ application to:

Prepare the scan process
Spawn a Python process to execute the scanner
Step 3 – Python Scanner Execution

The Python scanner begins execution immediately after being launched by C++.
A sequence of predefined security checks is executed in order.

For each check:

A PowerShell command is executed
The system configuration result is captured
The output is structured and prepared for evaluation
Step 4 – Security Rule Evaluation

Each collected result is evaluated against hardcoded security rules in the Python scanner.

The scanner determines:

Whether the configuration is secure or insecure
The associated severity level
Step 5 – JSON Result Construction

After all checks complete, the Python scanner constructs a JSON object.

Each finding includes:

Finding ID
Severity
Description
Evidence (raw or interpreted output)
Recommended remediation

The JSON output is written and returned to the C++ application.

Step 6 – Result Processing (C++)

The C++ application reads and parses the JSON output.

Parsed data is used to:

Populate the UI with findings
Group findings by severity
Calculate summary statistics
Step 7 – Report Generation

The C++ application generates an HTML report using the parsed results.
The report is saved locally and reflects the completed scan.

4. Implemented Security Checks (Current)

The following checks are actively implemented and executed by the Python scanner.

4.1 Windows Defender Status

PowerShell Command:

Get-MpComputerStatus | Select-Object AMServiceEnabled

Evaluation Logic:

Enabled → Secure
Disabled → High Severity
4.2 Windows Firewall Status

PowerShell Command:

Get-NetFirewallProfile

Evaluation Logic:

All profiles enabled → Secure
Any profile disabled → Critical Severity
4.3 SMBv1 Protocol

PowerShell Command:

Get-WindowsOptionalFeature -Online -FeatureName SMB1Protocol

Evaluation Logic:

Disabled → Secure
Enabled → High Severity
4.4 Remote Desktop (RDP)

PowerShell Command:

Get-ItemProperty -Path "HKLM:\System\CurrentControlSet\Control\Terminal Server"

Evaluation Logic:

Disabled → Secure
Enabled → Medium Severity
4.5 BitLocker Encryption

PowerShell Command:

Get-BitLockerVolume

Evaluation Logic:

Enabled → Secure
Disabled → High Severity
4.6 User Account Control (UAC)

PowerShell Command:

Get-ItemProperty -Path HKLM:\Software\Microsoft\Windows\CurrentVersion\Policies\System

Evaluation Logic:

Enabled → Secure
Disabled → High Severity
4.7 User Account Check

PowerShell Command:

Get-LocalUser -Name Guest

Evaluation Logic:

Disabled → Secure
Enabled → Medium Severity

This check evaluates the status of built-in user accounts, including the Guest account.

4.8 Local Administrators Group

PowerShell Command:

Get-LocalGroupMember -Group Administrators

Evaluation Logic:

Output is reviewed for:
Unexpected accounts
Excessive privilege assignments
Severity is assigned dynamically based on findings
4.9 Remote Access Configuration

PowerShell Command:

.\rremote_enabled.ps1

Evaluation Logic:

Remote access enabled → Medium Severity
Remote access disabled → Secure
