8. Security and Ethical Constraints (Enforced)

The system currently enforces the following constraints:

All checks are read-only
No automatic remediation is performed
No sensitive user data is stored
Execution is intended for authorized systems only
9. Current Testing Status

Testing is focused on validating implemented functionality, not planned features.

Validated areas include:

Accurate detection of configuration states
Correct severity classification
Successful Python → JSON → C++ data flow
Proper handling of permission-related failures
Successful HTML report generation

A set of 10–15 test cases is currently used to validate behavior.

10. Current Completion Status

The system currently:

Executes a full scan from UI → Python → PowerShell → JSON → UI
Detects multiple Windows security misconfigurations
Classifies findings by severity
Displays results in the interface
Generates a complete HTML report
11. Error Handling

The system includes structured error handling across all layers to ensure stability during scan execution.

PowerShell Layer:

Errors are captured using PowerShell error handling mechanisms
Scripts are configured to stop execution on critical failures

Python Scanner:

Wraps PowerShell execution in try/catch blocks
Captures command execution failures and unexpected output
Returns error states as part of the JSON response

C++ Application:

Validates JSON input before parsing
Handles missing or malformed fields gracefully
Displays error messages in the UI when scan issues occur

All detected errors are included in the scan output to ensure transparency and aid debugging.

12. Prerequisites

The following requirements must be met for proper system operation:

Administrative privileges are required to execute most PowerShell security checks
The application (CLion or compiled executable) must be run as Administrator
Windows PowerShell must be available and enabled
Python runtime environment must be properly configured

Failure to meet these requirements may result in incomplete or failed scans.

13. File Structure

The project uses a structured directory layout for organizing components:

/powershell/
- Contains all PowerShell scripts used for system checks

/python/
- Contains the Python scanning engine

/cpp/
- Contains the main C++ application

/build (e.g., cmake-build-debug)/
- PowerShell scripts must currently be accessible from this directory at runtime

Note:
Due to current implementation constraints, PowerShell scripts are required to reside in or be copied to the build directory for execution.

